One way to find the n-th smallest element in an array without using sort or extra memory is to use the Quickselect algorithm. 

Here's an outline of how the algorithm works:

1. Choose a pivot element from the array (e.g., the first element).
2. Partition the array around the pivot:
   - Move all elements smaller than the pivot to the left of the pivot.
   - Move all elements larger than the pivot to the right of the pivot.
3. If the pivot index is the n-th smallest element, we're done.
4. If the pivot index is less than n, repeat the process on the right subarray.
5. If the pivot index is greater than n, repeat the process on the left subarray.

Here is the C++ code for Quickselect:

```
// Returns the n-th smallest element in arr[l..r]
int quickselect(int arr[], int l, int r, int n) {
    if (l == r) {
        return arr[l];
    }

    // Choose the first element as pivot
    int pivot = arr[l];

    int i = l + 1; // index for elements smaller than pivot
    int j = r;     // index for elements larger than pivot

    // Partition the array around the pivot
    while (i <= j) {
        if (arr[i] <= pivot) {
            i++;
        } else if (arr[j] > pivot) {
            j--;
        } else {
            std::swap(arr[i], arr[j]);
        }
    }

    // Place the pivot in its final position
    std::swap(arr[l], arr[j]);

    // Check if pivot is the n-th smallest element
    if (j == n-1) {
        return arr[j];
    } else if (j < n-1) {
        // Repeat on the right subarray
        return quickselect(arr, j+1, r, n);
    } else {
        // Repeat on the left subarray
        return quickselect(arr, l, j-1, n);
    }
}

// Sample usage
int arr[] = {5, 2, 9, 1, 7};
int n = 3; // find the 3rd smallest element
int result = quickselect(arr, 0, 4, n);
std::cout << "The " << n << "-th smallest element is: " << result << std::endl;
```

